# Agent Memory System

Memories are stored as `.cursor/rules/*.mdc` files with `alwaysApply: true`. They persist across all sessions.

## When to Create a Memory

Proactively save a memory when any of these come up during work:
- **Architecture patterns** — how systems are built (e.g., RLM pattern, data flow)
- **Codebase conventions** — naming, file structure, styling patterns
- **Key decisions** — why something was built a certain way, trade-offs chosen
- **Domain knowledge** — business logic, user-facing concepts, data models
- **Team/project context** — who works on what, project goals, integrations
- **Tech stack details** — versions, configurations, gotchas
- **User preferences** — Aurel's coding style, UI opinions, workflow habits

## How to Save

1. Create a new `.cursor/rules/<topic-slug>.mdc` file (one topic per file, under 50 lines)
2. Use `alwaysApply: true` unless the memory only matters for specific file types
3. Keep content concise and factual — no filler
4. After saving, briefly tell Aurel what was stored (one sentence)

## How to Update

- If new info relates to an existing memory file, update that file instead of creating a new one
- If a memory becomes outdated, update or remove it

## Naming Convention

`<topic-slug>.mdc` — lowercase, hyphenated. Examples:
- `mitable-rlm-architecture.mdc`
- `db-schema-conventions.mdc`
- `ui-design-system.mdc`
- `agent-chat-patterns.mdc`
